 and Northgate, it's still there, the shop. And there was a shop called Stewarts. And Bainbridge Barkers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did they have clubs as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well it - you could go with this card to those shops you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did you have new shoes any time or were they secondhand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
Oh no, they were new shoes. But they were mended 'til there was nothing left on them. My father used to - mend them from all sorts of bits of leather he use
d to get hold of, I don't know where he got it from but - he used to mend our shoes, and he always used to fill them with studs in those days, kind of boot protectors and you used to go to a shop and they were a penny a card. And they were steel things an
d he used to always fill our school shoes with these and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did it make them heavy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
Well it didn't make them heavy so much as slippery. We always used to fall about a lot because - they were always filled with these studs so that you wouldn't wea
r them down to the leather you see and it was save him - and in those days, which you couldn't do now, he used to get patches put on your shoes if the uppers used to go. Oh yes, you used to go and get - which reminds me, were coming past this little cobbl
e
rs shop on Saturday, my husband and I - and it was this little cobblers shop and I said to my husband, I can remember going there with shoes and - boots we wore in those days and I said, I used to take this cobbler boots and I used to think to myself, oh 
h
e'll never mend these. 'Cos father used to put the - leather part on and all this man got about our shoe repairs or boot repairs was the patches he had to put on you see. And in those days we used to kick the toes out a lot. And he used to put a new to ca
p
 on. Or if you - if you did them at the side you would get a - a - a leather - patch put on your shoes. Just stitch them on, with a little machine, yes. Nowadays you - you throw them away don't you. Oh you would - you would never go - you wouldn't take th
e
m. But it - that's what you had to do in those days. There were a lot of children without any shoes or stockings at all, I can remember quite - clearly children staying away from school because - if it was - snowy or stormy weather - because they hadn't a
ny shoes or boots fit to come - yes. I can remember - many children without shoes and stockings in the wintertime in Darlington.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Where would they come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 They used to sell newspapers in the poorer parts of the town. Round Park Street and if yo
u went to the town on a - Saturday evening, all the newsboys - no shoes and stockings, barefooted and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Was Darlington }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 quite}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  a poor town then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Certain parts of it was. Park Street and John Street, all that part and - they were very well know
n, there was music hall jokes about those parts. There was a ragged school in Darlington you know. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 What was a ragged school actually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well there was a Mr Anwick used to run this school. Anwick, J Anwick used to run this school and a Mi
ss Berry, and she used to have a pawnshop in Darling - in the main street in Darlington, her father. And, they used to run this ragged school, it was a kind of Sunday school in the Leadyard you know, round by St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 Cuthbert\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  church there, just behind there. 
And - all the Sunday schools in the town - everyone went to Sunday school in those days - and about a fortnight or three weeks before Christmas they would ask you all if you had any old clothes. And if you had you used to take them to Sunday school on thi
s particular day and then they were all sent to this - ragged school and there was always a distribution of clothes to the children that went }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 there}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Was it just a Sunday school they went to or did they go every day to this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh no, no, it 
was just on a Sunday they went. Yes. Yes. The very poor children and they used to get a distribution of clothes every now and again. Or books or - or - anything, toys or anything you see. And he ran it for years and years, 'til I expect there was no more 
need to do it after the - in fact, he ran it until after the first world war. Right up. It was a - an institution - everyone knew about the ragged school in - yes. Yes. Yes. Yes, he did a lot of work along the poor children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Where were your shoes bought when they were new?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
Well used to be a - a shop called Stewarts on the Stonebridge. Yes, and he used to sell - I would say cheap shoes. Strong boots in those days. Some of them used to have what we called - steel toecaps on for my brothers, you know
, like caps on so that you wouldn't kick the toes out so quickly at school. And - most of our shoes were bought there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 When did you have new shoes, was that at Easter and Whit week the same as the clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh aye, we just got them when we absolutely needed them, when they absolute must.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did your father help hour mother with any of the jobs in the house, the cleaning for instance, did you ever see your father cleaning?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well he used to have to help when mother was ill which he used to be
, she used to have very - suffer an awful lot from biliousness and - until I was old enough. And that was at a very young age, she used to have to - help, yes. Otherwise - otherwise he wouldn't have time, he used to work twelve hours a day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 How often was she ill with this biliousness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh - sometimes every fortnight, every - every fortnight, if she went three weeks that was a - a long time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Would she be ill for a few days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Yes. She was - she was ill for two or three days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did your father help with the cooking at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No, he was never in you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did he ever help with the washing up?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No, no, because he was absolutely exhausted when he came home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did he light the fires at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well he used to work one shif
t on nights and one shift on days and - and sometimes when he came in - on a morning, if he wasn't too tired - especially in the wintertime when it was very cold, he would light the fire when he came in, sometimes he was so exhausted he went straight to b
ed. Sometimes he used to - if it was very cold, he used to light the fire so we would have a fire to come down to when we got up in the morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did your father do any decorating or repairs to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did he do any improvements to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 No money to do those sorts of things.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did your father ever dress or undress you or bath you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No, I don't remember my father doing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did he ever read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did he tell you stories at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 You mean in the sense of reading stories to us?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did he ever tell you stories, things he remembered or making up stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh yes, he would tell us things that happened to him when he was a child. And - things that happened - that he thought were inte
resting to us, he would tell us about them. But I never remember him telling us a story in the sense that I would call it a story, no. No. No, he'd tell us old things and customs and - things like that, but in the sense of reading a book or - or - althoug
h he was a very - he read quite a lot, my father, but - he never - I never remember him telling - reading us a story or - or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did he ever take you out without your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Where did you used to go?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 He used to take us for walks. And - mostly on a Sunday. Sometimes on a Sunday morning. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 This was when I was very, very small, before we had so many in family, when there were maybe just - two or three of us and - that he could take. He used to take us for walks and - on a Sunday mo
rning, that was the only time he had free of course. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
And - as a very great treat I can remember - in the summer - on a Sunday afternoon he would walk us over - from Darlington over Monkhead Wood, Stapleton, Monkhead Woods to Croft. And - he would take some
 bread and butter sandwiches or - what my mother had, and we would have our tea and then we would take the train back from Croft to Darlington. Oh, do you know, we used to look forward to that, that was a great treat in those days. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 Because we never travelled - very rare travelled by the trains. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
In fact very rare, although there were trams in Darlington, we very rare traveled on a tram because that would cost money. And we walked. Or - wherever we wanted to go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 It was quite a long way to walk though wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 It was about three miles that walk but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Your mother stayed at home did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh yes, my mother stayed at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 You got on the train from Croft?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh we forgot to get out once. Five minutes, that's all it used to take and y
et it used to be the highlight of the afternoon, coming home in a train for five minutes. And as a very great treat, in Darlington in those days, there was a Theatre }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 Royal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  which s where the ABC is now. And there was a Hippodrome which is a Civic - Civic Theatre is. And - there used to be very good shows come there. We used to get Carl - The Carl }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 Rosa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  Opera Company used to come every year. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 
The D'Oyley Carte - the Carl Rosa was heavy - heavy operas like Faust and those sort of things. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 But the Doyle Carte was 
- light operas - Gilbert and Sullivan and - light things. And then there were variety shoes. And there was a Shakespearian company used to come every season in Darlington. Yes. And then there was a - and then we used to have variety shows. Now, my father 
u
sed - when there was anything good on my father used to take us to the - Hippodrome they called it in those days. And we used to go - be there for seven o'clock and we didn't come out 'til ten, but there used to be an interval, father always used to go ou
t and have a drink at the interval and he was - I was always go in the gallery and it was only tuppence a seat in the gallery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 You had to queue up for that to get it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Yes. It used to be full in those days. And this happened maybe - in the wintert
ime, we never went in the summertime but - in the wintertime maybe once a month he would take us there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did your mother not go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No. Well she always had children to look after you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Who went then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Just my father and me and another 
brother went. When it got more of us that was cut out altogether because it would cost too much wouldn't it. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 You'd look forward to that too wouldn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Very much so, yes. Yes. Yes, and they were really very - you know, well known artists
 used to come you see, they used to tour the provinces and it was - they had a very flourishing - Theatre Royal and - all with quite good things, things that I can remember and have remembered that have brought me pleasure right through my life, rememberi
ng them and the - yes. Oh it was - it sounded - it maybe life sounded very drab when you come to think of the material things of life but in little pleasures we had, you know - it's surprising. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 Weren\rquote t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  the miserable life by any means.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did your father e
ver look after you when your mother was out, did your mother ever go out and sort of leave you in your father's hands at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 My mother didn't go out very much, but I can remember - she - and she did this - more or less - oh for years and years. On a
 Sunday night my father would stop in and she used to - go to see - a brother of my father's and his wife, who she was very friendly with. And she used to put the baby to bed after - tea and she used - that was her little escape. Looking back over the yea
rs, she used to go and see them and have her supper with them and I expect tell them all her trials and tribulations and then she used to come back home. And that's all I can remember me mother ever going to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 And your father looked after you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
Oh yes. Until I was old enough to do it. Yes. But father very rarely went out on a Sunday night. He always used to go out on a Saturday night but he didn't go out on the Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 That was your mother's night out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did you have any tasks that you had to carry out regularly at home to help hour mother and father, I should imagine you had plenty?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
Oh - I - I had a very - looking back - I had a very hard childhood life - because - being the eldest, and also the only girl you see. I ha
d to learn to do things form - awfully early age. And - for instance - our living room floor was covered with linoleum, or oilcloth as they used to call it in those days, but on top of those we had big rugs - mats made with clippings. Now, in the winter t
ime, every wintertime you always had a - a big two yards by a yard and a half, mat to do. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 What are clipping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well you - all coats and things, you clip them. Yes. And you used to have to crab them you see and you had a pair of frames, we had
n't any frames, but the lady next door had some, and I know my mother used to get a sugar bag from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 stores}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  in}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492  those days which was made of}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13503492  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 Hessian}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 . And she used to cut it down and - sew it all together and this was the canvas that we used to do - and be
fore we could go out to play in the winter, as soon as ever we were - I knew how to do that I should think when I was - oh, four or five. Because you see, you would see your father and mother doing it and you - think - oh, I might do this. Very little of 
that because as soon as you - as soon as you - as soon as we could do it and you got proficient at it - you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
 never able to go out to play until you did so many - a square so big of this mat and - I know today, even in church I go to, they have - they ma
ke these mats. The farm people evidently - I thought they were way out but they don't. But they couldn't get me to put a - yes, you made your own rugs you see. That was a winter occupation. You - you knit - socks. I learnt to knit socks when I was - oh I 
couldn't tell you how young. And you not only knit socks but you pull - when the foot was worn out you pulled them out down to the heel and then you - instead of buying the wool for a new pair of socks you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 refooted}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  them you see. And my father wore all hand 
knitted socks you see. And so you refooted them. You always had knitting on the go. There was always patching to do and socks to mend and I always had those jobs to do every night before I could - could go out. And as I say, I left school when I was - twe
l
ve, before I was thirteen, when I was about twelve and a half I left school. And I used to be able to bake for - when I was twelve year old, bake bread and - teacakes and - I had to, I washed for the family when I was twelve. I did really, and it was wash
i
ng in those days. I think having these experiences when you're young, you think, oh well, now when I'm old enough I'm not - I'm going to have something better than this. That seems to be - was my - I loved school and I had to leave it and I'd have loved t
o have been a teacher. And could have been one if it had - but I had to leave school, still - you see, determined that you're not going to put up with that kind of thing all your life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did you ever help with the cleaning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh yes, I did the cleani
ng, I did every job in the house by I was twelve I could wash and bake and shop - I knew every joint of meat by I was a fairly early age because I used to - I had all the shopping to do. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 
Because my mother had these - always had babies on the go as - and - 
I can remember when I was at school in those days, all the children used to do the shopping, I mean, your mother wanted any meat before you went to school you had to go for it to the stores you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Or very often if there was a lot there you were late. Now
 - if you were late at school when I was at school the headmistress used to stand in the yard to ten minutes past nine. The bell was rung at five minutes to nine, you used to go in at nine. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15554908\charrsid13503492 
And the headmistress used to stand in the school 'til ten past - n
ine and all the latecomers used to - she used to get them in the school and then she used to march them in to her room and you got a wallop with the stick on your hands and it made you smart, used to go to the tap and - really smart and - that used to - o
h - because it wasn't my fault - really. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 It was something that I couldn't help and I felt that I shouldn't - have had that. But there you are. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 How long did you continue to do these tasks at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh right up 'til I was married. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did your brothers have any special tasks to do at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well they all got jobs as soon as ever they were able, part time jobs. They all had to. One used to work for - a fruiterer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 While he was at school you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh yes, they all had jo
bs. One used to work for a milkman. Two used to work for a milkman. I can remember my elder - my eldest brother used to work for this fruit man and he used to go at half past seven on a morning and work 'til school time. And then he used to go in the even
i
ngs and work 'til eight. And then he used to go all day on a Saturday. And he used to get - five shillings a week. For doing that. Yes. I don't know whether he did get five shillings a week or not. And my eldest - my eldest brother - oh, it wouldn't be fi
v
e shillings a week for that. And - and my eldest brother, when he was fourteen he left school and he was apprenticed to the motor trade. He was a motor mechanic. And he used to go at half past seven in the morning 'til five at night and - and he had seven
 
and six a week when he started work. I can remember my husband now had - the first job he had he had four and six a week and he was - heating rivets. At Stimpsons for four and six a week from half past seven in the morning 'til five at night and on a Satu
rday 'til one o'clock. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did your brothers have any special jobs at home that they had to carry out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
Well used to have to do the so much - so - if we were making mats they had to do that. They only had to chop - learn to chop the sticks and - 
suchlike and in those days - in the wintertime they used to have to - coke was much cheaper than coal and - and coal was only ninepence a hundredweight in those days. But coke was cheaper to burn than coal, and I know - I know my father made my brothers a
 
- I think they called them bogeys in those days - and you could go to the - gas works in Darlington and get coke cheaper you see. So they used to have to go there on Saturday and get coke for the fire which - burnt longer and made a hotter fire than coal.
 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 It sa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 ved coppers, but there you are you see, they counted you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Your sisters were quite a bit younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
Oh yes. Oh they always had to help in the house with the washing up and the mending and suchlike. But not as much as me because things probably got a bit easier then you see, my brothers had jobs and - that made things a bit easier.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did he two baby brothers have any jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well they - no, they got off the easiest of them all 'cos things were getting better then. Conditions were get
ting better and - a bit better and - and - there was more to do the chores then you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did the older children help the younger with things they found difficult such as dressing or eating, or look after them in other }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 ways}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well I think in a big
ger family you do that, you - you - you - you have to. I mean, if there's a baby you learn to feed it and what it feeds on. At a very early age I could look after a baby, change its napkins, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 
and make}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  its food. Had to because when my mother was - ill, it was me that had to do it from a very early age. I liked that part of - at home - because I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 like}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 looking}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
 after babies. And I knew all there was to know about babies, long before - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did he younger children help the older ones in any ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well I can't - how could they really. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well all the children went to bed at seven o'clock, the younger ones, they were all - that was the only quiet time your parents had I su
ppose, when you were young you were in bed by seven o'clock. Even my parents were always in bed by ten.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Your father would have to get up early wouldn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 He had, he started work at six o'clock in the mornings 'til six o'clock in - at night. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed before you could put yourself to bed?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 My mother used to put us to bed, yes.;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Do you remember at what age you put yourself to bed?;
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 I couldn't remember that. It would be very young. And then I - then of course I got the job of putting them to bed. Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did you share a bedroom with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Did you share a bed with anyone? Could you tell me what the sleeping arrangements of the whole family were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
My mother and father had the front room and if there were any babies they were cots - they were in there. In the back room there were - two double beds. So the family slept in the - back room. There were three in a bed - sometimes. The boys. And I slept w
ith a younger brother sometimes. And then - well I always had a brother sleeping with me until I was - oh - what - thirteen, fourteen But I slept in the same room with them. You had to, no one thought anything about it like these days - those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 In front of the fire, oh yes. Yes. There was nowhere else to do it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 
Friday night was bath night, used to have a big zinc bath and there was a boiler arrangement at the side of the fire which always had hot water in by the way. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
We used to - yes, there was a - an oven at one side and a - a water boiler at - the fire in the middle and a water boiler at the other side. So you always had hot water. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 
And my mother used - well, my father used to put the big pan - a big iron pan on there , the fires, straight after tea on a Friday and this boiler was always topped up. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 
And then we had a bath. In front of the fire on a Friday. That was the only bath we had in the week. We used to get our - what we called our hands and face and knees washed
 before we - we went to bed in the - in the evening and - we always changed our clothes then, our stockings and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 You had clean clothes to put on after }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 bath night}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Yes. Yes. My father - my mother used to - always in the water that - the last wat
er that was finished with she always used to wash all our stockings in that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 So as not to waste the water?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No. And they were put in the oven next to the fire when the oven wasn't on -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 You were telling me about the socks in the oven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Yes. Yes, they were dried and - we used to put them on again the next morning. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 In the living room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Were there }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 any occasions}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  when they ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 On the - range in the living room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 You burnt coal or coke?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Coal or coke, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 there an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492  oven at all anywhere else, any gas cooker or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 No. No other means of cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 When was breakfast eaten, what time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Before we went to school. Half - between - about quarter past eight to half past eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 What members of the family were present?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well my mother and all the children, father was at work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 How did your father manage for his breakfast, it depended on his shi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 f}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 t did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 Well he worked - do you want to know about now. Well my father worked a twelve hour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 shift. One week he worked from six o'clock in the morning 'til six o'clock in the evening. And the other week he worked from six o'clock in th
e evenings 'til six o'clock the next morning. And on a Saturday he worked from six o'clock 'til one o'clock. Lunch time, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9001745 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 So how would he manage for breakfast then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8342232 EE  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14499774\charrsid13503492 My father had always had - I can remember this quite well - the night befor
e my mother or me, when I was old enough, used to - fry my father two sandwiches of bacon. Put - the bacon was put between - two slices of bread and it was put in a tin box and we used to make him a - a can of tea and that was done the night before. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3549181\charrsid13503492 He use
d to get up at quarter past five in the morning - he never used to have anything before he went out but he used to take his breakfast with him and he used to have - oh I think - at least a mile and a quarter to walk from our house to his place of work. }{
